Covariation

While variation describes the behavior within a variable, covariation describes the behaviour between two variables. Covariation is the tendency of the values of two or more variables to vary together in a related way. The best way to spot covariation is to visualise variations between two or more variables.

library(tidyverse)
library(nycflights13)
library(emo)
library(naniar)
library(ggstance)
library(lvplot)
library(patchwork)

A categorical and continuous variable

We may want to see the distribution of a continuous variable broken down by a categorical variable. We may want to use a normal freqpoly, but this wouldnt be very useful for this comparison, because the height of the lines are given by the count, hence if one group is much smaller than the others, itll be hard to see the differences in the shape. For example;

ggplot(diamonds, aes(price)) +
  geom_freqpoly(aes(colour = cut), binwidth = 500)

In the above, its hard to see the difference in distribution because the counts vary very well. To make the comparison better, given that our goal is to compare different distributions across categories, what we can do is to have the y-axis shown as the density, which is the count standardised so that the area under each frequency polygon is 1

diamonds %>%
  group_by(cut) %>%
  summarise(prices = median(price, na.rm = T))
#> # A tibble: 5 x 2
#>   cut       prices
#>   <ord>      <dbl>
#> 1 Fair        3282
#> 2 Good        3050
#> 3 Very Good   2648
#> 4 Premium     3185
#> 5 Ideal       1810

ggplot(diamonds, aes(price, y = ..density..)) +
  geom_freqpoly(aes(colour = cut), binwidth = 500) +
  scale_colour_brewer(palette="Set1")

With the above plot, I can see and compare the distributions across the different categories, and intepret them. Like from the above plot, I can see that fair diamonds (low quality) has the highest average price. Boxplots are another alternative to display a continuous variable broken down by a categorical variable. A boxplot stretches from the 25th percentile to the 75th percentile, a range known as the Interquantile range (IQR). The middle of the box is a line showing the median (50th percentile). Points are plotted outside the boxplot edges, these are points that fall over 1.5 times from either edges of the IQR (i.e over 1.5 times below the 25th percentile, and/or over 1.5 times outside the 75th percentile). These points are seen as unusual (outliers), hence why theyre plotted individually.

So to make a boxplot of the distribution of price for each cut category

ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut, price)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Looking at the plot above, and comparing with that of the freqpoly plot earlier, with this one, I also see that a better quality diamond are cheaper on average than fair diamonds (lowest qualiity)

The levels used by cut has an intrinsic ordering (good, very good, fair, etc), and we can use reorder function to reorder the boxplot. And the cut factor already had its levels ordered in an order I like;

levels(diamonds$cut) # I can reorder this using reorder
#> [1] "Fair"      "Good"      "Very Good" "Premium"   "Ideal"

I cant plot ggplot values in a ggplot2 plot, and so, to visualise this, I know that when dep_time is NA, it means the flight was cancelled, but theres usually a scheduled time, so I can use that to know flights whose departure time is missing.

flights_sched <- flights %>%
  select(dep_time, sched_dep_time) %>%
  mutate(cancelled = is.na(dep_time),
         sched_hours = sched_dep_time %/% 100,
         sched_mins = sched_dep_time %% 100,
         sched_dep_time = sched_hours + sched_mins / 60)
 
ggplot(flights_sched, aes(cancelled, sched_dep_time)) +
  geom_boxplot()


ggplot(flights_sched, aes(sched_dep_time, colour = cancelled)) +
  geom_freqpoly()
#> `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

I see that flights thatre cancelled usually have a late scheduled departure time. And therere few cancelled flights cases.

4. One problem with boxplots is that they were developed in an era of much smaller datasets and tend to display a prohibitively large number of outlying values. One approach to remedy this problem is the letter value plot. Install the lvplot package, and try using geom_lv() to display the distribution of price vs cut. What do you learn? How do you interpret the plots?
ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut, price)) +
  geom_boxplot() 


ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut, price)) +
  geom_lv(aes(fill = ..LV..))

Basically, Letter-value plots are boxplots for large datasets, while normal boxplot is useful for showing small data sets (n < 200). When using a boxplot for large datasets (~ 10,000 - 100,000), the number of outliers grows linearly with the sample data (usually wrongly labelled as outlier in this case), also, the estimates of tail behaviour are not displayed, even though these large sample sizes means estimates on the tail are more likely to be genuine extreme observations, or true outliers as would be labelled by a boxplot. Letter-value plots are a variation of boxplots where the whiskers are replaced with a variable number of letter values, selected based on the number of observations. Any values outside the outermost letter value (note that each box above is coloured different by the letter it represents), is displayed individually and is what is considered outlier by this plot. These modifications reduce the amount of outliers we see in a boxplot for large datasets, and conveys more reliable information about the tails, and outliers are the most extreme values only. See the documentation for more info, or the paper here (Ill still have to look at it more)
